<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-569-214  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 569 214.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  August 21 1989 v15 n17 p39(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Waiting out a poly plethora. (polysilicon) ( Special Report)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Worldwide capacity for production of polysilicon is 60 percentgreater than demand.andP;  US suppliers, who are not deeply into themarket, are hurt by the glut.andP;  Overcapacity favors those with alonger view and deeper commitment to the market, namely theJapanese.andP;  Japanese corporations' claims have grown from 10percent 10 years ago to almost 30 percent in 1989.andP;  That figurewill probably grow to almost 40 percent by 1991.andP;  The good newsfor poly customers is that prices will continue to decline: since1974, rates have been almost halved.andP;  The poly makers themselvesare either giving up altogether like Texas Instruments Inc andMotorola Inc or updating technology in hopes of higher margins.andO;Ethyl Corp seeks a 15 percent return on investment using a newprocess that produces poly pellets more efficiently.andP;  Ethylproduces 1,250 metric tons per year, with capacity enough todouble that production.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SupplyIntegrated CircuitsJapanese CompetitionProduction.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablegraph.andO;Caption:   Polysilicon capacity for US, Japan, Europe. (table)Consumption vs. capacity. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>